{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508572"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:06:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:06:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2807"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2807","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2807"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.05,0.68,0.2,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2784"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111093"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2784"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2807"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93216"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"3341"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3732"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3775"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41934"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45144"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111093"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27 year old man presents to the Emergency Department with several hours of feeling generally unwell, with excessive sweating and anxiety. He also describes having muscle spasms. He has a medical history of asthma and depression. His regular medications are salbutamol inhalers and fluoxetine. He binge drinks alcohol several times per week, and last night at a friend\u0027s birthday party had six beers, five vodka-mixers and tried a tablet of ecstasy (MDMA). He is normally a non-smoker but at the party last night he tried some cannabis mixed with tobacco. He felt short of breath afterwards and used his salbutamol inhaler (without spacer) to some effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable, is visibly shaky and sweating. His blood pressure is 135/78 mmHg, pulse 122/min and regular, temperature 37.1\u00b0C, respiratory rate 12/min and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 99% on room air. His pupils constrict and converge appropriately, but are grossly dilated bilaterally. Neurological examination reveals hypereflexia in the lower limbs with several sustained beats of clonus at the ankles. Strength is 5/5 bilaterally, tone and coordination are intact.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for his symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Salbutamol overdose","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Serotonin syndrome","MDMA intoxication","Alcohol withdrawal"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis man is likely suffering from \u003Cstrong\u003Eserotonin syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. This is due to overstimulation of serotonergic receptors in the central and peripheral nervous system, causing autonomic dysfunction (sweating, tachycardia, mydriasis, hypertension), altered mental status (restlessness, anxiety) and neuromuscular excitation (tremor, hyperreflexia, clonus). It is often caused by new antidepressant use or increase in dosage, or by ecstasy/MDMA use. This is likely a mild-moderate presentation and would be managed by immediately discontinuing his serotonergic medication, supportive care, a period of observation and monitoring and advice to avoid this party drug in the future.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESalbutamol overdose\u003C/strong\u003E is an important differential in anyone with a history of use. This can present similarly with the tachycardia, tremors and diaphoresis, however would not explain his hyperreflexia, clonus, mydriasis and muscle spasms. The half-life of salbutamol is relatively short, and the doses he administered last night have likely worn off but the time of presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeuroleptic malignant syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is an adverse reaction to dopamine antagonists such as antipsychotics. This would present more gradually than serotonin syndrome and be expected to cause diffuse rigidity and decreased deep tendon reflexes. This is made less likely also by the lack of neuroleptic medications in the patient\u0027s history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOngoing\u003Cstrong\u003E MDMA intoxication \u003C/strong\u003Eis an important differential given the history of MDMA use. This can cause restless legs, jaw clenching, tachycardia, hypertension, hyperthermia and agitation. Continued intoxication by itself would not explain the hypereflexia and mydriasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcohol withdrawal\u003C/strong\u003E can cause a similar presentation to the above, but we would expect a more chronic drinking history and a longer sober period to onset of symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Serotonin syndrome is a potential complication of antidepressant use.","Serotonin syndrome presents with the triad of autonomic dysfunction, altered mental status and neuromuscular excitation."],"references":["Wang RZ, Vashistha V, Kaur S, Houchens NW. Serotonin syndrome: Preventing, recognizing, and treating it. Cleve Clin J Med. 2016 Nov;83(11):810-817. doi: 10.3949/ccjm.83a.15129. PMID: 27824534. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27824534/","Kalant H. The pharmacology and toxicology of \u0022ecstasy\u0022 (MDMA) and related drugs. CMAJ. 2001;165(7):917-928. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC81503/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93216"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2807"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93216"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-08T19:44:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-08T19:44:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2784"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111093"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attri